---------------------------------------------------------------------
5.1 CSEG1032 COMPUTER ORGANIZATION AND ARCHITECTURE
---------------------------------------------------------------------

Unit I Digital computers:
Prompt:
"Teach COA Unit I deeply: computer block diagram, buses, number systems, complements, signed arithmetic, floating-point, RTL, micro-operations, ALU."

Unit II Basic organization and instruction format:
Prompt:
"Explain instruction formats, addressing modes, stack organization, instruction cycle, interrupts, and compare IA-32 vs ARM in beginner-friendly way."

Unit III Control unit organization:
Prompt:
"Teach hardwired vs microprogrammed control units, control memory, address sequencing, and RISC vs CISC with diagrams and comparison table."

Unit IV Memory organization:
Prompt:
"Teach memory hierarchy, cache mapping, RAM/ROM types, hit/miss, write policies, and cache coherence with solved numerical examples."

Unit V Input-output organization:
Prompt:
"Explain I/O organization, interfaces, interrupt types, programmed I/O, interrupt-driven I/O, DMA, and priority interrupts with real use-cases."

Unit VI Pipelining:
Prompt:
"Teach pipelining concepts, hazards, handling methods, speedup, throughput, and compare pipeline behavior in different processor styles."


---------------------------------------------------------------------
5.2 CSEG1033 DATA STRUCTURES AND ALGORITHMS
---------------------------------------------------------------------

Unit I Introduction + arrays + complexity:
Prompt:
"Teach DSA Unit I with asymptotic analysis, amortized idea, arrays, structures, ADTs, memory allocation and recursion vs iteration tradeoffs."

Unit II Linked lists:
Prompt:
"Teach all linked list variants and operations with memory diagrams, complexity table, and common coding errors in C."

Unit III Stack and queue:
Prompt:
"Explain stack/queue/deque/priority queue with array and linked list implementation and applications (expression eval, DFS, BFS)."

Unit IV Trees:
Prompt:
"Teach trees deeply: traversals, BST, AVL rotations, red-black concept, B-tree, heap and heapsort with visual walkthrough."

Unit V Hashing and graphs:
Prompt:
"Teach hashing, collisions, load factor, graph representation, BFS/DFS, connected components, shortest path and MST fundamentals."

Unit VI Sorting and searching:
Prompt:
"Explain sorting/searching algorithms with stability, in-place property, lower bound concept, complexity comparison and practical selection guide."


